I"^3<p>A few days ago, India celebrated its National Science Day which marks the scientific achievement of Sir C. V. Raman and also inspires many Indians to pursue science. In 1996, government budget for research and development was 0.65% of GDP while same was decreased to 0.65% of GDP in 2015 <sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>. For year 2018-19, even after financial boost, it was around 0.8% of GDP <sup><a href="#ref2">2</a></sup>. Government is trying to boost research by providing incentives like a financial reward for the publication. Although such schemes have received mixed responses from the Indian scientific community <sup><a href="#ref4">4</a>, <a href="#ref5">5</a></sup>, there is no proper data regarding scientific advances in India. Hence I decided to check it by myself.</p>

